    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-20T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-20T22:00:00-05:00" n="227"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d227">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8899: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-21T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 21, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 21—4:36 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>310. My 306, July 20, 4 p.m., paragraph 7.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Vice Minister Hsu Mo asked me July 21, 10 a.m., to communicate to the
                        American Ambassador the personal hope of General Chiang Kai-shek that Mr.
                        Johnson will come to Nanking in order that he may exchange views with him
                        more promptly and directly. The Vice Minister asked me to maintain secrecy
                        in regard to this message from General Chiang.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The German Embassy and possibly other International Settlement missions
                        have been informed by the Chinese Foreign Office in more emphatic terms than
                        before that it is the hope of the Chinese Government that Chiefs of Mission
                        will return as soon as possible to the capital.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Sent to the Department, Peiping.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
